name: cyclohexane, 1,1,2-trimethyl-
Reason: The base compound cyclohexane has a melting point of 6.5°C. Each methyl group generally decreases the melting point due to the introduction of bulk, which can disrupt the crystalline packing and lower the melting point. For a mono-substituted methyl group, the decrease might be around -10°C. Since there are three methyl groups, one of them being on the same carbon as another (geminal), the combined effect of the first two could be around -20°C (since the geminal substitution introduces more steric hindrance and thus decreases the melting point further, let's estimate that as -12°C for the two). The third methyl group is less hindered and could be estimated to have a -8°C effect.
